ABUJA – The Federal Capital Territory Administration (FCTA) has demolished shanties, illegal shops under high tension wire in Sauka, Airport Road. The Special Assistant to the Minister on Monitoring, Inspection and Enforcement, Comrade Ikharo Attah, also dislodged illegal markets located at the entrance of Sauka community. He said the market contributed to the perennial traffic gridlock at Sauka end of the airport road. Ghana, Rwanda, Senegal Partner BioNTech to Produce Vaccines Labor Market Dominates U.S. Earnings Calls -Goldman Kostin Attah made this known immediately after the demolition of illegal shops and shanties as a demonstration of commitment to holistic sanitation along the Airport Expressway, being one of the most strategic gateways to Abuja. His words, “We came here to actually commence the cleanup of airport road, it is a multidimensional cleanup exercise. We need to remove some things impeding the beauty of the airport road corridor. Being Abuja gateway connecting the northern and southern wings. “We have been able to get intense cooperation from the people living here, especially the indigenous community. We cleared some potion where many person has left and filled the road. As well as working on the road a little subsequently we also remove all attachments under high tension wires, you remember Kubwa that petrol disaster. “We are hopeful that the work won’t be much because we are still going to clear the outside. We are hopeful to do what the FCT Minister directed us that every activities should come inside the community, the illegal market must move to the main Sauka market.”